        {
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 1,
                "prefix": 4.0,
                "text": "Role & Responsibilities within the Trust"
            },
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 29
        },
        {
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 1,
                "prefix": 4.1,
                "text": "Infection Prevention and Control Site Committee (IPCC) are responsible for the review of this policy at least every three years, but more frequently if there are changes to Infection Prevention and Control Legislation or guidance."
            },
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 30
        },
        {
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 1,
                "prefix": 4.2,
                "text": "Role & Responsibilities of Individuals within the Trust"
            },
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 31
        },
        {
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 0,
                "text": "Duties Are:"
            },
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 32
        },
        {
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 1,
                "prefix": 4.3,
                "text": "The Chief Executive has overall responsibility for the implementation of this policy. The Chief Executive delegates this responsibility to the Director for Infection Prevention and Control."
            },
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 33
        },
        {
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 1,
                "prefix": 4.4,
                "text": "Director for Infection Prevention and Control (DIPC) has the responsibility to ensure there are adequate resources and expert clinical guidance available to manage infection prevention and control across the MSE. The DIPC also has the responsibility to ensure timely and appropriate management of exposure incidents at the hospital."
            },
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 34
        },
        {
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 1,
                "prefix": 4.5,
                "text": "The Head of Infection Control MSE will act on legislation, national policies and guidance ensuring effective policies are in place and audited in relation to Measles"
            },
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 35
        },
        {
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 1,
                "prefix": 4.6,
                "text": "Infection Prevention and Control Team (IPCT) responsibilities are to:"
            },
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 36
        },
        {
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 0,
                "text": "Promote evidence-based infection prevention and control practices in line with Trust policies"
            },
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 37
        },
        {
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 0,
                "text": "Follow up contacts of a clinically suspected or laboratory confirmed case of measles identified within the hospital setting"
            },
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 38
        },
        {
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 0,
                "text": "Be responsible for the production of the policy and management procedures"
            },
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 39
        },
        {
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 0,
                "text": "Liaise with the Occupational Health Department if the screening and vaccination of staff is required."
            },
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 40
        },
        {
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 0,
                "text": "Support the East of England Health Protection Team in managing contacts in the community, who were exposed to a case whilst at the hospital."
            },
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 41
        },
        {
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 1,
                "prefix": 4.7,
                "text": "The Infection Control Doctor and Consultant Microbiologist are responsible for providing advice on the diagnosis of measles."
            },
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 42
        },
        {
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 1,
                "prefix": 4.8,
                "text": "Clinical Site Managers are responsible for organising patient movements to isolation rooms with an en-suite facility"
            },
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 43
        },
        {
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 1,
                "prefix": 4.9,
                "text": "Occupational Health Department have responsibility to:"
            },
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 44
        },
        {
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 0,
                "text": "Review MMR status of new staff and follow up and monitor exposed staff as clinically necessary."
            },
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 45
        },
        {
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 0,
                "text": "Appropriate management of care of staff members"
            },
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 46
        },
        {
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 1,
                "prefix": 4.1,
                "text": "Employees have the responsibility to:"
            },
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 47
        },
        {
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 0,
                "text": "Adhere to this policy and procedures"
            },
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 48
        },
        {
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 0,
                "text": "Ensure the contact use of PPE"
            },
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 49
        },
        {
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 0,
                "text": "Ensuring that they are up to date with their vaccinations"
            },
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 50
        },
        {
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 0,
                "text": "Attend relevant training as appropriate to their individual role"
            },
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 51
        },
        {
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 0,
                "text": "Identify  to  their  line  manager  any  problems  or  failings  associated  with  the management of confirmed or suspected measles cases"
            },
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 52
        },
        {
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 0,
                "text": "Promptly report all incidents concerning the risks or exposure to measles in accordance with the Trust's Incident Reporting Policy"
            },
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 53
        },
        {
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 1,
                "prefix": 5.0,
                "text": "General information on Measles"
            },
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 54
        },
        {
            "type": "table",
            "sequence_num": 55,
            "data": {
                "num_rows": 3,
                "num_cols": 2,
                "table_items": [
                    {
                        "text": "Communicable Disease"
                    },
                    {
                        "text": "Measles is an acute, highly infectious viral illness that is comparatively rare in the UK following introduction of the measles, mumps & rubella (MMR) vaccine in 1988. However, if vaccine coverage falls below 90% in a community at any one time, the probability of outbreaks is substantially increased."
                    },
                    {
                        "text": "Clinical Condition Measles rash Koplick spots"
                    },
                    {
                        "text": "Measles remains a potentially highly dangerous disease in hospitals. This is partly due to the risk to susceptible immuno- compromised patients but also due to the fact that it is highly infectious. The incubation period is between 7\u201318 days (average 10-12 days) but may be prolonged to 21 days in the immunosuppressed. A prodromal phase (early warning signs) of two to four days starts with fever, conjunctivitis, cough, coryza (runny nose) and Koplik spots on the buccal mucosa (spots inside the mouth, in line with the molars). Exposed individuals are highly infectious from the beginning of this prodromal phase to four days after the appearance of the rash. The rash is made up of red or brown blotches which flow into each other. It usually starts behind the ears and spreads downwards over the face, neck and body and lasts 5-6 days. Other symptoms may include diarrhoea, vomiting and abdominal pain."
                    },
                    {
                        "text": "Confirmation of Diagnosis"
                    },
                    {
                        "text": "If you suspect a patient has measles : Ask patient to wear a surgical mask Isolate the patient in a side room Take a throat swab for PCR Take blood for measles serology Inform the Consultant Microbiologist The Consultant Microbiologist is available at any time to discuss the clinical management of cases, especially those in immunocompromised patients or where complicated disease is"
                    }
                ]
            }
        },
        {
            "type": "table",
            "sequence_num": 56,
            "data": {
                "num_rows": 5,
                "num_cols": 2,
                "table_items": [
                    {
                        "text": ""
                    },
                    {
                        "text": "present Contact Public Health England: 0300 303 8537 option 1, or 01245 444417 out of hours to inform them of the suspected case Inform The Infection Prevention & Control Team during working hours for isolation advice Because of the rarity of measles and the fact that other conditions can produce similar rashes, it is essential to confirm the diagnosis virologically. This includes bloods for antibody testing and a viral throat swab for PCR testing."
                    },
                    {
                        "text": "Mode of transmission"
                    },
                    {
                        "text": "The virus is transmitted via respiratory droplets that become airborne during coughing or sneezing, or via direct contact with respiratory secretions. Spending more than 15 minutes with someone infected with measles is sufficient time to transmit measles. In a susceptible (non-immune person) less than 15 minutes exposure to a case can lead to disease."
                    },
                    {
                        "text": "Notifiable disease"
                    },
                    {
                        "text": "Measles remains a notifiable disease under the Health Protection Legislation (England) Guidance 2010, (Public Health England, 2010) and therefore the Consultant for Communicable Disease Control (CCDC), Public Health England must be informed about all suspected or confirmed cases All suspected cases should be promptly notified by phone, both in hours and out of hours, without awaiting laboratory confirmation. This is to avoid delays in organising crucial post exposure prophylaxis to prevent infection in contacts. The IPCT should also be informed of all clinically suspected or confirmed cases of measles."
                    },
                    {
                        "text": "Isolation"
                    },
                    {
                        "text": "Admission of patients with measles should be avoided where possible. If admission is essential the patient must be isolated immediately in a single room with an ensuite, and doors must be kept closed. A Source Isolation Sign must be displayed on the door, gloves, apron must be worn by all staff entering the room and FFP3 mask if MMR status is unknown. If possible only staff whose immune status is known should enter the room; these should be kept to a minimum. Take only equipment into the room which is necessary; clean all equipment using Clinell Universal wipes and place linen into a red alginate bag then into a white linen bag."
                    },
                    {
                        "text": "Precautions required"
                    },
                    {
                        "text": "Precaution is required until 4 days after the onset of the rash."
                    }
                ]
            }
        },
        {
            "type": "table",
            "sequence_num": 57,
            "data": {
                "num_rows": 5,
                "num_cols": 2,
                "table_items": [
                    {
                        "text": "until"
                    },
                    {
                        "text": ""
                    },
                    {
                        "text": "Staff immunisation"
                    },
                    {
                        "text": "Staff who has clinical or social contact with patients should be known to be immune to, or immunised against measles."
                    },
                    {
                        "text": "Contacts"
                    },
                    {
                        "text": "Those born before 1970 are likely to have had measles and be naturally immune. However, immuno-suppressed individuals of all ages and those born after 1970 may be at risk. A list of probable patient and staff contacts should be made, and an assessment made as to whether prophylaxis with Human Normal Immunoglobulin (HNIG) or MMR vaccination should be offered within 72 hours of contact, based on level of risk and contact time. Individuals are infectious from 1 day before the beginning of the prodromal symptoms (usually about 4 days before rash onset) until 4 full days after the rash appears. Less than 15 minutes exposure or face to face exposure of any length to a case can lead to disease in a susceptible (non-immune) person. Detailed guidance on assessing susceptibility and doses of post exposure prophylaxis is given by Public Health England: Guidelines on post exposure prophylaxis for measles. (Public Health England, [August] 2017) Click here to open guidance"
                    },
                    {
                        "text": "Susceptible staff"
                    },
                    {
                        "text": "The immune status of staff who have attended the patient needs to be established in co-operation with the Occupational Health (OH) Department. A list of staff should be generated and emailed to the Occupational Health Team where records will be checked. Staff who require appointments will be informed individually and should attend OH as requested (appointments will be given as a priority)."
                    },
                    {
                        "text": "Visitors"
                    },
                    {
                        "text": "Clinical staff should explain the risk of Measles exposure to visitors A history of measles infection or 2 doses of MMR immunisation is considered evidence of immunity Close contacts of the patient who are not immune could potentially be incubating the infection and should be advised against visiting. Contact the IPCT for advice"
                    }
                ]
            }
        },
        {
            "data": {
